name: Canzone
comments: This song was first presented at the XVIII Festival di Sanremo 1968 held at the Sanremo Casino in Sanremo between February 1 and 3, 1968. According to the rules of this edition every song was performed in a double performance by a couple of singers or groups. In this case by Adriano Celentano and Milva. Don Backy, a member of the Clan Celentano , wrote the song and planned to sing it at the Sanremo Festival. Backy left the clan following a spat with Celentano, who in turn forced Backy to give up his place at Sanremo in favor of himself. Moreover, it is said that Celentano's arrangement and performance were purposely half-hearted, to undermine the commercial success of the song.

name: Who's Gonna Buy Your Chickens
comments: This American folk song is a bit of a mystery. Alledgedly, Paul Clayton recorded Mary Bird McAllister in his log cabin (Brown's Cove) in '58/'59. It's supposed to be registred at the Archive Of Folk Culture of the Library of Congress in Washington, DC under number AFS 11,866-11,868 (unconfirmed). There are McAllister recordings by Clayton filed under AFC 1961/004, but no song titles are available. Also, it's potentially the same song that was published in 1923 "Eight Negro Songs (From Bedford Co., Virginia) as "Who's Gon Bring You Chickens" (unconfirmed).

Lyrics go: "I want a little sugar in my bowl, I want a little sweetness down in my soul, I could stand some lovin', oh so bad, feel so funny, I feel so sad. I want a little steam on my clothes, maybe I could fix things up so they'll go. What's the matter daddy, come on, save my soul, I need some sugar in my bowl, I ain't foolin', I want some sugar in my bowl. You been acting different I've been told. Soothe me, I want some sugar in my bowl."
